    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-03-17T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-03-17T03:00:00-05:00" n="551"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d551">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">761.93/1749: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-03-17T15:00:00+07:00"
                            >March 17, 1944—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received March 17—2:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>479. Consul [at] Tihwa<note n="4" xml:id="d551fn4">Horace H. Smith.</note>
                    reports he is informed by Foreign Affairs Delegate<note n="5" xml:id="d551fn5"
                        >Chaucer H. Wu.</note> that on March 11, 10 planes bearing clear Soviet Star
                    markings, bombed provincial troop concentrations in Altai region 25 kilometers
                    southwest of Chingho (which does not appear on Embassy’s maps), 75 kilometers on
                    Chinese side of Mongolian border, with smaller raids next 2 days. Total
                    casualties under 30. Delegate stated Soviet Consul General resented his
                    implication of possible Soviet responsibility but promises to transmit his
                    formal protests to Moscow. Delegate suggesting joint Sino-Soviet investigation
                    on the spot.</p>
                <p>Unconfirmed information from a local source (said to emanate from Sinkiang
                    Provincial Government) states bombing planes were Soviet planes and Chinese
                    forces attacked were putting down Kazak uprising, Foreign Office was said to be
                    making inquiries through its Moscow Embassy.</p>
                <p>Political Vice Foreign Minister<note n="6" xml:id="d551fn6">K. C. Wu.</note>
                    tells us the “rumor” does not in his opinion seem credible but Soviets have been
                    acting very independently lately and telegraphic inquiry being made of Sinkiang
                    Government. His attitude in response to our inquiry was evasive.</p>
                <p>Tihwa being instructed to keep us fully informed.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Moscow.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
